 to the Judge, Ray recalls lengthy courtroom battles over lines of evidence, historical interpretation, and philosophies of history, reflecting on the problems inherent in teaching history in the adversarial courtroom setting. Told with charm and based on extensive experience, Telling It to the Judge is a unique narrative of courtroom strategy in the effort to obtain constitutional recognition of Aboriginal and treaty rights.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aEvidence, Expert -- Canada -- Biography. 0aEvidence, Expert -- Canada. 0aHistorians -- Canada -- Biography. 0aIndians of North America -- Legal status, laws, etc. -- Canada. 0aRay, Arthur J. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / Native American Studies.2bisacsh1 aHutchins, Peter W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTeillet, Jean, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2011-2010z978311127414008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2011 - 2010z978311127721940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077358647540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773586475423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773586475/original  a978-3-11-127414-0  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2011-2010c2010d2011  a978-3-11-127721-9  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2011 - 2010c2010d2011  aGBV-deGruyter-alles